article.description:
Allen Iverson and the Philadelphia 
76ers were in control.  So they did not have to worry about a
game-winning shot by David Wesley and the New Orleans Hornets.

article.headline: Iverson (29 points) on top of his game in victory
article.linkText: Iverson, 76ers pound Hornets to improve to 8-0 at home
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Larry Brown has coached Allen Iverson in all but one of the superstar's six NBA seasons, and says he's never seem him play better.
Iverson

Iverson had 29 points on 11-of-20 shooting as the Philadelphia 76ers avenged an earlier loss to New Orleans with a 108-87 victory Monday night that extended their home record to 8-0. ''The thing that is exciting me is he's trying to do the right thing every time down,'' Brown said. ''His all-around game is as good as anytime I've been around him.'' Iverson played one of his best games, making 7-of-9 free throws and dishing out four assists. Several other spectacular passes went unconverted by his teammates. He says his improvement has actually come on the defensive end. ''I'm being as hard on myself on defense as I've been in offense,'' Iverson said. ''Before I was concentrating so hard on getting a good shot. Now I am working hard at both ends of the court.'' Todd MacCulloch had 15 points, Keith Van Horn and Aaron McKie 14 apiece, and Eric Snow had 12 points and 10 assists for Philadelphia. The 76ers last won eight straight at home in 2000. The win avenged a 99-98 buzzer beater loss in New Orleans Nov. 19, the only loss for the 76ers in their last eight games. ''We definitely wanted to send those guys a message,'' McKie said. ''We knew we let one get away (in New Orleans).'' Jamal Mashburn, who had a season-high 37 points in the last game against the 76ers, scored 18 Monday night, but only two in the second half. Baron Davis added 17 points and Jamaal Magloire 11 for the Hornets, who had a three-game losing streak snapped. ''We were just a step slow tonight,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. ''We just didn't have it. If you have an off day that doesn't mean you didn't play well.'' A 3-pointer by Davis pulled the Hornets within 78-71 early in the fourth quarter. But a fastbreak layup by Iverson and five straight points by McKie paced a 12-0 run and extended the lead to 19 points. Philadelphia scored 13 of the first 17 points of the third quarter to pull ahead 69-51 to match its biggest lead. Iverson had five points and Van Horn four during the run. The Hornets did not make a basket in the last 4:47 of the third but still cut the deficit to 10 points by making 9-of-10 from the foul line. The 76ers led by as many as 18 in the first half, but Mashburn scored 16 points in the final 6:25 to help the Hornets pull within 56-47 at the break. ''I got into a rhythm for a while, I just couldn't sustain it,'' Mashburn said. Game notes
Mashburn was held scoreless for the first 17:35 of the game but made his first seven shots in the second quarter. ... Van Horn left the court early in the fourth quarter after being hit in the chin with an inadvertent elbow in a crowd while going for a rebound. He returned with his chin bandaged and got three stitches after the game. ...The 76ers outrebounded New Orleans 44-30, an important stat because the Hornets are 25-1 when they get more rebounds than Philadelphia.
